[cweb][Title]Coast Redwoods[/Title][center][i][url=cweb://wiki]Go Back[/url] [/i][b]Coast Redwoods[/b][br][i]Encydia[/i][br][hr][br][/center][left][b]Coast redwood trees[/b] are among the tallest and oldest living organisms on Earth, found along the misty coasts of northern California and southern Oregon. These conifers can grow over 350 feet tall, with trunks so wide that a grown person could stand inside some of the largest. Their reddish-brown bark, which can be up to a foot thick, protects them from fire, insects, and disease, allowing these ancient trees to survive for centuries.[br][b]The redwoods' unique relationship with fog[/b] helps them thrive in a climate that is often cool and wet. Their needle-like leaves are able to capture moisture directly from the air, supplementing the rainwater they absorb through their roots. This fog drip can provide up to one-third of a redwood forest's water supply, making it essential for their growth and the dense ecosystem they support.[br][b]Redwood forests[/b] are vibrant habitats for countless species, from birds and mammals to mosses and fungi. The fallen giants and hollowed trunks create microhabitats that support life at all levels of the forest. [i]Beyond their ecological importance, coast redwoods play a critical role in sequestering carbon dioxide, helping combat climate change and maintain the health of the planet.[/i][/left]
